1. Stemming vs Lemmatization
- Stemming → Cuts words blindly  
  Example: "running" → "runn" ❌  
- Lemmatization → Uses dictionary  
  Example: "running" → "run" ✅  

👉 MCQ Trick: “Which gives real word?” → Lemmatization

2. CBOW vs Skip-gram
- CBOW → Context → predict word  
- Skip-gram → Word → predict context  

👉 MCQ Trick:  
- Faster → CBOW  
- Better for rare words → Skip-gram  

3. BERT vs GPT
- BERT → Bidirectional (left + right)  
- GPT → Unidirectional (left → right)  

👉 MCQ Trick:  
- Understanding tasks → BERT  
- Text generation → GPT  

4. Perplexity
- Measures how confused model is  

👉 MCQ Rule:  
- LOW perplexity = GOOD model  
- HIGH perplexity = BAD model  

5. N-grams
- Unigram = 1 word  
- Bigram = 2 words  
- Trigram = 3 words  

👉 MCQ Trick:  
“I love NLP” → Bigram = (I love), (love NLP)

6. POS Tagging vs NER
- POS Tagging → grammar (noun, verb)  
- NER → real-world entities (person, location)  

👉 MCQ Trick:  
"Apple" →  
- POS = noun  
- NER = organization  

7. Static vs Contextual Embeddings
- Static (Word2Vec) → same meaning everywhere  
- Contextual (BERT) → meaning depends on sentence  

👉 MCQ Trick:  
"bank" → different meanings → only BERT handles it

8. Language Model Goal
👉 Predict next word  

Example:  
"I love pizza with ___" → cheese  

9. Tokenization vs Sentence Segmentation
- Tokenization → split into words  
- Sentence segmentation → split into sentences  

10. Stopwords
- Common words removed  
  Example: the, is, and  

👉 MCQ Trick: improves efficiency but may remove meaning

11. Word Embeddings
- Words → vectors  

👉 MCQ Trick:  
king - man + woman ≈ queen  

12. Ambiguity Types
- Lexical → word meaning  
- Syntactic → sentence structure  

13. Transformers
- Use attention mechanism  
- Do NOT process sequentially like RNN  

14. Pretraining
- Train on large data first  
- Then fine-tune  

👉 MCQ Trick: does NOT require labeled data initially  

LAST MINUTE REVISION
- BERT → both directions  
- GPT → left to right  
- CBOW → context → word  
- Skip-gram → word → context  
- Perplexity ↓ = better  
- Lemmatization > Stemming  
- NER ≠ POS  
- Transformers use attention

